The Thyssen industrial group cut  pre-tax losses by 65 percent in the first half of the year to 182 million  marks (114 million dollars) from 515 million marks in the first half of last  year, the company said on Wednesday.
Sales were unchanged at 16.4 billion marks.
Overall losses had been reduced owing to a big cut in losses by the steel  division, the company said.
Orders booked had increased by four percent to 17.5 billion marks from  16.8 billion marks and the company said that it expected to see "a marked  improvement in sales and results in the second half of the year".
Restructuring in all divisions was bearing fruit.
For the whole of 1992-93 the group had reported net losses of 994 million  marks compared to a net profit of 350 million marks.
